/* Comparison with Western secularism */ Removed the phrase 'accepts religious law over government institution'. Nowhere does India accept religious law over the government. The article cited by Smith does not state that either. Even it the West, the state maintains financially historical religious monument. Such as the French law of 1905 states that religious monuments created before 1905 will be wholly maintained by the state financially.

The references cited do not state that 'religious law supersede state law'. Indian constitution does not state that and parliament can legislate on anything as long as it does not violate freedom of religion (like banning triple talaq). Furthermore, the [[Hindu code bills]] have nothing 'religious' about them and are part of common law. They are secularized to the point of complete similarities of texts between them and the special marriage act. The only religious law is the Muslim Personal Law.
